    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-08T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-08T16:00:00-05:00" n="711"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d711">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/521</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Willard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-08T21:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 8, 1918, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 8, 4.26 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1053. Embassy’s 1052, February 7, 5 p.m. Upon learning yesterday of Lasteyrie’s
                    proposed departure, the King immediately sent <pb facs="0833" n="1667"
                        xml:id="pg_1667"/> for him, and, according to French Ambassador, stated that
                    the United States was trying to force Spain to inject the shipping and tonnage
                    question into Spanish-American agreement; that if United States insisted, both
                    Spanish-American and French-Spanish negotiations were at an end; but that if,
                    however, this point was dropped by the United States he would do his best to
                    secure ratification of French-Spanish agreement and did not doubt but that he
                    would be successful.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Willard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
